child_comments.text: @heisenberg___y he's accelerating the car without telling her when he's doing it. I do this to people riding in my tesla for the first time, too, and it's hilarious to see their reactions, and I dont even have the performance version.
@gooniesneversaydie so thereâs no sound! Itâs quiet when you are driving it or even sending it full throttle and again more so these cars have instant power!

@rez.iian21 it's not instant, it's linear. People need to stop saying "instant", there is no "instant acceleration", just like there's no "instant displacement" or "instant velocity". It's linear. Acceleration is the derivative of velocity and hence is the chance in velocity between at least 2 instances in time, which precludes it from being "instant". Same goes for Powe. Power by definition is work over a certain amount of time. Sorry, this has been bugging me for a while now. #rantover
@gooniesneversaydie so what ur saying is itâs instant power
@gooniesneversaydie theres a difference between instantaneous power and average power

@m_emara53 there is also a difference between instantaneous and instant. When people say "instant acceleration/power/torque", they are referring to the sensation of  experiencing linear acceleration/power/torque. Exponential acceleration/power/torque can be just as instantaneous as linear, but it's experienced as "slower", because it's, well, exponential. So sorry, but it is what it is. You integrate the area under the curve and initially there will be more area under the linear curve.
@gooniesneversaydie itâs correct to say instant torque tho

@dixplode only if you also apply it to ICE Vehicles, sure, then you can somewhst generalize it. But people don't say it about ICEs... People perceive ICE torque as "delayed", it's not, it's simply exponential. Just look up a graph of "linear vs exponential" and you'll see. You'll also see thta at some pint the graphs conclude, at which point the Ice engine would surpass the torque of an EV. These are of course approximate, but the basics of ICE vs EV are that.
@dixplode when you look at the graphs, you see both start "instantly", just one increases linearly and one exponentially.

@gooniesneversaydie when people say instant torque it means instant peak torque. It doesnât mean ICE doesnât have torque instantly, it just means it needs a lot of ramping up before it reaches peak torque...
@dixplode there's quite a difference between "instant" and "peak". Actually not even related much... One is an magnitude and one is a value in time...
@gooniesneversaydie electric motors in EVs reach their peak torque instantly, period.
@dixplode yes, they do. Never said they didnt?! ð¤
